    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Clojure on Mac &amp; Emacs]]></title>
    <link href="http://avallark.github.com/blog/2012/05/31/clojure-on-mac-and-emacs/"/>
    <updated>2012-05-31T13:09:00+02:00</updated>
    <id>http://avallark.github.com/blog/2012/05/31/clojure-on-mac-and-emacs</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>First you need to get "lein". Lein is a tool that lets you manage your projects in clojure. Lein also has a REPL that lets you run clojure directly.</p>

<p><em>Disclaimer: Some of you have tried copy pasting and noticed that emacs throws out errors in code. This is because octopress uses opening and closing quotes in my themes. Simply replace all single and double quotes with the normal quotes and they will work just fine.</em></p>

<pre><code>~$ wget https://raw.github.com/technomancy/leiningen/stable/bin/lein
</code></pre>

<p>This will download lein into your home directory. Once downloaded, move it to ~/bin directory. Add bin directory to your <strong>PATH</strong> environment variable and then finally make this file executable using the following commands.
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>~$ mkdir ~/bin
</span><span class='line'>~$ mv lein ~/bin
</span><span class='line'>~$ export PATH=$PATH:~/bin #put this into your .bashrc
</span><span class='line'>~$ chmod u+x ~/bin/lein</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
Once this is done, run lein with the following command
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>~$ lein repl 
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
This command is to get a REPL command line to run your clojure code. When run for the first time, it will try to find clojure and if it doesn't find it installed, then it will download clojure and install it and return you the following shell
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>user=&gt; 
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
Write your first clojure program by typing  <em>(println "hello, world")</em> into this shell. You can type <em>(exit)</em> to exit.</p>

<p>There you go, now you have clojure and lein installed.</p>

<p>Now you need to configure your emacs to use this setup. I am going to use SLIME and swank-clojure. First let us install swank-clojure plugin to lein.
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>~ $ lein plugin install swank-clojure 1.3.4
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
This command should end with :
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>Including clojure-1.2.1.jar
</span><span class='line'>Created swank-clojure-1.3.4.jar
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
Now add the ~/bin to execution path within your .emacs file. (anywhere)
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>(setenv "PATH" (concat (getenv "PATH") ":~/bin"))
</span><span class='line'>(setq exec-path (append exec-path '("/sw/bin")))
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
I prefer using slime for my lisp! sweet sweet slime. It is important that you do not have your old slime, its known to create problems. I would recommend commenting out the old slime load instructions on your .emacs.  To load slime, all you need is clojure-mode.el from
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>https://github.com/jochu/clojure-mode
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
and add the following lines in your .emacs
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
<span class='line-number'>7</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>(add-to-list 'load-path "~/.emacs-local/clojure-mode")
</span><span class='line'>(require 'clojure-mode)
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
This is all you need.</p>

<p>Now on your command prompt you could use lein to create a new project.
<div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'><div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
<span class='line-number'>2</span>
<span class='line-number'>3</span>
<span class='line-number'>4</span>
<span class='line-number'>5</span>
<span class='line-number'>6</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class=''><span class='line'>&lt;/p>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;pre>&lt;code>$ lein new first-project
</span><span class='line'>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>
</span><span class='line'>
</span><span class='line'>&lt;p></span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div>
This will create a new directory called <em>first-project</em> in your current directory.</p>

<p>Open emacs, go to eshell and cd to the directory of the project. Once you are there type</p>

<pre><code>M-x clojure-jack-in
</code></pre>

<p>and thats it!! you will have SLIME ready to go!</p>

<p>"hack and glory await"</p>
